**No validation for zero or negative durations**

`time.ParseDuration` successfully parses negative values (e.g. `"-1h"`) and zero (`"0s"`). If `JWT_REFRESH_EXPIRY` is set to a negative or zero duration, `time.Now().Add(s.refreshExpiry)` in `generateTokenPair` will produce an expiry in the past, silently causing every issued refresh token to be immediately expired. Adding a minimum positive check after a successful parse would prevent this silent misconfiguration:

```go
if d, err := time.ParseDuration(value); err == nil {
    if d > 0 {
        field.SetInt(int64(d))
    } else {
        // treat non-positive as invalid and fall through to the fallback
        envTag := fieldType.Tag.Get("env")
        defaultValue := fieldType.Tag.Get("default")
        slog.Warn("Non-positive duration for config field, using tagged default",
            "field", envTag, "value", value, "default", defaultValue)
        if fallback, fallbackErr := time.ParseDuration(defaultValue); fallbackErr == nil {
            field.SetInt(int64(fallback))
        }
    }
} else {
    ...
}
```

