**CE deployments default to `true`, enabling "fail open" for EE routes**

The new second operand evaluates to `true` whenever `LICENSE_ENFORCEMENT_ENABLED` is **not** explicitly set to `"false"` — including when the variable is entirely absent. In practice this means any vanilla CE deployment that sets neither `ENABLE_PAID_ENTERPRISE_EDITION_FEATURES` nor `LICENSE_ENFORCEMENT_ENABLED` will have `SERVER_SIDE_ONLY__PAID_ENTERPRISE_FEATURES_ENABLED = true`.

The fast-path guard in `ee/layout.tsx` now passes unconditionally for these deployments, so EE route access is gated solely by the runtime `fetchStandardSettingsSS()` call. That call is wrapped in a `try/catch` that **fails open** (returns `children`) on any error:

```ts
} catch (error) {
  // If settings fetch fails, allow access (fail open for better UX)
  console.error("Failed to fetch settings for EE check:", error);
}
return children;
```

Previously, a CE deployment would be hard-blocked by the fast-path constant before any network call was ever made. Now a transient settings-API error silently grants full access to EE admin routes (user groups, analytics, RBAC, etc.).

Consider logging or handling the fail-open case more conservatively, or at least explicitly documenting this risk in the code comment so future contributors understand the security trade-off.

