**Mac guide dialog unmounted before user can see it**

When a Mac user clicks "Enable" in the banner and permission is already granted (or becomes granted), the `enable()` function calls `updateSettings({ enableChatCompletionNotifications: true })` on line 34 of `useEnableNotifications.ts` **without awaiting it**. It then immediately calls `setShowMacGuide(true)`.

Because the promise is not awaited, React re-renders before the IPC call completes. When `settings.enableChatCompletionNotifications` flips to `true` in the cache, `NotificationBanner` re-evaluates the early-return guard on lines 11–16 and returns `null`, unmounting the entire fragment including `MacNotificationGuideDialog`. The user either never sees the dialog or sees it only briefly before it disappears.

**`ChatCompletionNotificationSwitch` doesn't have this problem** because it always renders its dialog regardless of the `isEnabled` state.

To fix, move the dialog outside the early-return guard:

```tsx
export function NotificationBanner() {
  const { settings, updateSettings } = useSettings();
  const { enable, showMacGuide, setShowMacGuide } = useEnableNotifications();

  const shouldShowBanner =
    settings &&
    settings.enableChatCompletionNotifications !== true &&
    settings.skipNotificationBanner !== true;

  const handleSkip = () => {
    updateSettings({ skipNotificationBanner: true });
  };

  return (
    <>
      {shouldShowBanner && (
        <SkippableBanner
          icon={Bell}
          message="Get notified when chat responses finish."
          enableLabel="Enable"
          onEnable={enable}
          onSkip={handleSkip}
          data-testid="notification-tip-banner"
        />
      )}
      <MacNotificationGuideDialog
        open={showMacGuide}
        onClose={() => setShowMacGuide(false)}
      />
    </>
  );
}
```

