Escaped backslash before closing quote causes the string to never close. The check `content[i - 1] !== '\\'` is a single-backslash test, but doesn't account for escaped backslashes. A string like `"path\\"` ends with an escaped backslash followed by a real closing quote. At the closing `"`, the guard sees the preceding `\` and thinks the quote is escaped, so `inString` remains `true` forever. Everything after that is treated as inside a string, and `findMatchingBracket` silently returns `-1`, skipping the entire `install_requires` block.

Fix by counting consecutive backslashes to determine if a quote is actually escaped:

```suggestion
    } else if (inString && ch === stringChar) {
      // Count consecutive backslashes before this char
      let backslashes = 0;
      let j = i - 1;
      while (j >= 0 && content[j] === '\\') { backslashes++; j--; }
      if (backslashes % 2 === 0) inString = false; // unescaped quote (even # of backslashes)
    }
```

